        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">An Atlantic City showdown</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          What happens when one of the world‚Äôs top gamblers takes on a casino mogul who despises losing, especially when that mogul happens to be Donald Trump? Meet Akio Kashiwagi, known in gambling circles as ‚ÄúThe Warrior,‚Äù a world-class baccarat player and successful Japanese real estate tycoon with rumored ties to the Yakuza. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/trump-akio-kashiwagi-casino-showdown-1990-millions-lost.png" alt="In 1990, Trump and Akio Kasiwagi had an epic and remarkably personal showdown in which millions of dollars changed hands in days" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>In 1990, Trump and Akio Kasiwagi had an epic and remarkably personal showdown in which a lot of money changed hands in a few days. Credits: News UK</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In the late 1980s and early ‚Äô90s, Trump had just opened three casinos in Atlantic City: the Trump Plaza (1984), Trump Castle (1985), and his crown jewel, the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-tajmahal-casino?source=website" target="_blank">Trump Taj Mahal</a> in 1990. Unseemly dubbed ‚Äúthe eighth wonder of the world,‚Äù the casino was valued at over $1B and came with a daily credit burden of nearly $3M in interest payments. Trump‚Äôs casino empire was hemorrhaging money. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          So, in classic Trumpian fashion, he staged a spectacle. He planned to invite Akio Kashiwagi, one of the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-biggest-gambling-whale-in-the-world?source=website" target="_blank">biggest gambling whales in the world</a>, to his casino to gain big. Kashiwagi had previously walked away with $20M from Australia‚Äôs Diamond Beach Casino, nearly bankrupting it, and on other occasions lost money at Steve Wynn‚Äôs Mirage in Las Vegas. He was known for playing marathon sessions, betting $200,000 per hand, sometimes gambling for over 80 hours straight.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>


