          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The house always triumphs</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Trump rolled out the red carpet: from a private jet to a penthouse suite with ocean views. Piles of $5,000 chips awaited on the casino floor, and a tower of chips worth $250,000. Trump even extended a $6M line of credit. The battleground was set. Within 30 minutes, Kashiwagi was up $1M. Over two days, he bagged $6.2M. Trump‚Äôs spectacle had backfired, and instead of saving the Taj, it deepened the crisis.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Still, Trump wasn‚Äôt done. He invited Kashiwagi back for a rematch, and this time he bet on a calculated strategy. Behind the scenes, Trump enlisted <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-jess-marcum?source=website" target="_blank">Jess Marcum</a>, a brilliant mathematician and RAND Corporation veteran who once modeled nuclear war probabilities. Marcum devised a plan to grind Kashiwagi down using the casino‚Äôs baccarat edge.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The plan was simple: trap Kashiwagi in a "<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-freeze-out?source=website" target="_blank">freeze out</a>." He would bring $12M and agree to play until he doubled or lost it all. Marcum's simulations showed that the house would eventually triumph if Kashiwagi stayed at the table long enough. After about 75 hours, Kashiwagi‚Äôs odds of winning would drop to just 15 percent.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Kashiwagi agreed without having read the fine print, at least informally. There was no judicial way to hold him to the plan, but Trump expected him to honor it. Kashiwagi returned to Trump Plaza. This time, the tables turned. Over six days of play, Trump clawed back $10M, recovering the previous $6M loss and netting another $4M. The math eventually triumphed. The media got the spectacle they were promised, and Trump, momentarily, tasted victory.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The last bet</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          The house wasn‚Äôt the one collapsing. Trump‚Äôs empire was sinking quickly. His casinos filed for bankruptcy by 1992. He narrowly avoided personal bankruptcy. And Kashiwagi wouldn't live to see any of it unfold.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/trump-taj-mahal-liquidation-sale-crowds-expected-60-days.png" alt="The Trump Taj Mahal liquidation sale is expected to attract hundreds of people each day during the 60-day sale" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>The Trump Taj Mahal liquidation was expected to attract hundreds of people each day during the 60-day window. Credits: Craig Matthews/Press of Atlantic City</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          After Trump, Kashiwagi kept gambling, dropping $10M in Vegas, another $5M in Europe. The Japanese real estate bubble burst, and his fortune evaporated. Sooner, the once-invincible baccarat warrior drowned in $131M of debt. Then, on January 3, 1992, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-akio-kashiwagi-found-dead?source=website" target="_blank">Akio Kashiwagi was found dead</a> in his home near Mount Fuji. Stabbed over 150 times, the case remains unsolved to date.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The clash between Kashiwagi and Trump was a window into the brutal logic of the gambling world and business itself. Casinos survive by exploiting mathematical margins, while gamblers chase streaks and flirt with ruin. </p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
